<exercise>
<introduction>
<p>
Now consider the family of polar graphs
<me>
  r = 1 + a\cos(\theta),
</me>
where <m>a</m> is some variable greater than zero. These are called <term>cardioids</term>, because they kind of look like hearts when they're graphed.
</p>  
</introduction>
<task workspace="3in">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Sketch graphs of these with <m>r</m> as a function of <m>\theta</m> with <m>a=0.5, 1, 1.5</m>. 
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task workspace="3in">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the graphs you sketched above to explain why the polar graphs have no inner loop if <m>a&lt; 1</m> and have inner loops when <m>a &gt; 0</m>. Also, check that this is true with Desmos of any other technology of your choice.
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>

</exercise>



